headline.main: ESPN Employees Say Racism Endures Behind the Camera

docs.abstract: On weirdness, whiteness and federal agents in Portland.
docs.snippet: On weirdness, whiteness and federal agents in Portland.
docs.lead_paragraph: “Naked Athena.” Have you heard of her? She’s the woman who was so christened after she strolled into a recent Portland protest — one that was ostensibly, crucially, about Black lives — stark naked, save a mask (kudos to that) and skullcap. She sat down with her legs wide, and proceeded to do some yoga poses. Some say she was putting herself between protesters and police, that she was turning the cultural sacredness of a white (or at least a white-passing) woman’s body into a shield against rubber bullets and tear gas.

headline.main: Who Gets to Be a ‘Naked Athena’?
headline.print_headline: Who Gets to Be a ‘Naked Athena’?

docs.abstract: And by the way, it’s “suffragist” not “suffragette.”
docs.snippet: And by the way, it’s “suffragist” not “suffragette.”
docs.lead_paragraph: As the story is often told, the path to women’s suffrage began ​in Seneca Falls, N.Y.,​ in 1848 and ended with the ratification of the 19th Amendment in 1920. Susan B. Anthony and Elizabeth Cady Stanton​ were the leaders of the movement. It granted all women in America the right to vote.

headline.main: Suffrage Isn’t ‘Boring History.’ It’s a Story of Political Geniuses.
headline.print_headline: Radical, Exciting And Relevant, Especially Now

docs.abstract: Planned Parenthood and the complexities of anti-racism.
docs.snippet: Planned Parenthood and the complexities of anti-racism.
docs.lead_paragraph: This week, Planned Parenthood of Greater New York announced that it would remove Margaret Sanger’s name from its Manhattan Health Center. The grounds were Sanger’s eugenic ideas and alliances, which for years have been highlighted by anti-abortion advocates and minimized by her admirers. Under the pressures of the current moment, apparently, that minimization isn’t sustainable any more.

docs.abstract: The street demonstrations that have shuddered through Portland for 54 consecutive nights have drawn out a complicated mix of emotions and grievances.
docs.snippet: The street demonstrations that have shuddered through Portland for 54 consecutive nights have drawn out a complicated mix of emotions and grievances.
docs.lead_paragraph: PORTLAND, Ore. — With a ski helmet and goggles on her head, Allison Hyder recounted how she had told relatives that she planned to stand at the rear of protests in downtown Portland. But, in the early hours of Tuesday, the grandmother of five found herself right up front, locking arms with other mothers dressed in yellow.

headline.main: Chaotic Scenes in Portland as Backlash to Federal Deployment Grows
headline.print_headline: Sent to Quell Unrest in Portland, Federal Agents Fan the Flames
